text.tspan: Implications for Further Research
Although the Central Board of Secondary Education (CBSE) has made it mandatory for
every school to have a full-time school counselor, only 3% of the private schools in the national
capital of Delhi-NCR had counselors in 2014 (ASSOCHAM, 2014). The researcher believes that
the need for school counselors during the COVID-19 pandemic is essential as the results of this
study indicate an increase in students' stress levels. The government must take steps to ensure
that every student has access to a counselor. Furthermore, the provision of a school hotline
number for students under stress and feedback sessions for online classes may help avoid
disastrous consequences of increased academic pressure during the lockdown.
Given the circumstances, more research is required to assess the feasibility of online,
open-book examinations to evaluate students in India. As the education system, in practice, often
engages in rote memorization methods and "cramming" information, a revised teaching
pedagogy focused on developing students' critical thinking abilities and promoting application-
based knowledge has become imperative in the modern world.
Based on the results of this study, the researcher also questions whether tuition classes
and coaching centers are more student-centered and understanding of the students' problems. In
India, students are increasingly seen enrolling in "dummy schools" (schools allowing students to
attend tutorials and coaching during school hours to focus on university entrance exam
preparations) to study in elite coaching centers training for university entrance examinations
(Shandilya, 2019). This may indicate higher educational standards and better facilities provided
